events.description: Byzantine Emperor Zeno is forced to flee his capital at Constantinople, and his general, Basiliscus gains control of the empire.

events.description: Gustav I of Sweden is crowned King of Sweden, having already reigned since his election in June 1523.
events.html: • 1528 – Gustav I of Sweden is crowned King of Sweden, having already reigned since his election in June 1523.[2]

events.description: Bayinnaung, who would go on to assemble the largest empire in the history of Southeast Asia, is crowned King of Burma.

events.description: The city of Belém, Brazil is founded on the Amazon River delta by Portuguese captain Francisco Caldeira Castelo Branco.
events.html: • 1616 – The city of Belém, Brazil is founded on the Amazon River delta by Portuguese captain Francisco Caldeira Castelo Branco.[4]

events.description: Federalist Thomas Pinckney appointed first U.S. minister to Britain.
events.html: • 1792 – Federalist Thomas Pinckney appointed first U.S. minister to Britain.[5]

events.html: • 1808 – John Rennie's scheme to defend St Mary's Church, Reculver, founded in 669, from coastal erosion is abandoned in favour of demolition, despite the church being an exemplar of Anglo-Saxon architecture and sculpture.[6]

events.description: The organizational meeting leading to the creation of the Wernerian Natural History Society, a former Scottish learned society, is held in Edinburgh.
events.html: • 1808 – The organizational meeting leading to the creation of the Wernerian Natural History Society, a former Scottish learned society, is held in Edinburgh.[7]

events.description: The Palermo rising takes place in Sicily against the Bourbon Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.
events.html: • 1848 – The Palermo rising takes place in Sicily against the Bourbon Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.[8]

events.description: The Royal Aeronautical Society is formed in London.
events.html: • 1866 – The Royal Aeronautical Society is formed in London.[9]

events.description: Yohannes IV is crowned Emperor of Ethiopia in Axum, the first imperial coronation in that city in over 200 years.
events.html: • 1872 – Yohannes IV is crowned Emperor of Ethiopia in Axum, the first imperial coronation in that city in over 200 years.[10]

events.description: The National Trust is founded in the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1895 – The National Trust is founded in the United Kingdom.[11]

events.description: The University of the Philippines College of Law is formally established; three future Philippine presidents are among the first enrollees.

entities.name: University of the Philippines College of Law

events.description: The United States House of Representatives rejects a proposal to require states to give women the right to vote.
events.html: • 1915 – The United States House of Representatives rejects a proposal to require states to give women the right to vote.

events.description: Both Oswald Boelcke and Max Immelmann, for achieving eight aerial victories each over Allied aircraft, receive the German Empire's highest military award, the Pour le Mérite as the first German aviators to earn it.
events.html: • 1916 – Both Oswald Boelcke and Max Immelmann, for achieving eight aerial victories each over Allied aircraft, receive the German Empire's highest military award, the Pour le Mérite as the first German aviators to earn it.

events.description: The Minnie Pit Disaster coal mining accident occurs in Halmer End, Staffordshire, in which 155 men and boys die.
events.html: • 1918 – The Minnie Pit Disaster coal mining accident occurs in Halmer End, Staffordshire, in which 155 men and boys die.[12]

events.description: Hattie Caraway becomes the first woman elected to the United States Senate.
events.html: • 1932 – Hattie Caraway becomes the first woman elected to the United States Senate.[13]

events.description: World War II: United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt creates the National War Labor Board.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt creates the National War Labor Board.[14]

events.description: World War II: The Red Army begins the Vistula–Oder Offensive.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Red Army begins the Vistula–Oder Offensive.

events.description: A Martin 2-0-2 and Douglas DC-3 collide over Boone County, Kentucky, killing 15 people.
events.html: • 1955 – A Martin 2-0-2 and Douglas DC-3 collide over Boone County, Kentucky, killing 15 people.[15]

events.description: Vietnam War: Operation Chopper, the first American combat mission in the war, takes place.
events.html: • 1962 – Vietnam War: Operation Chopper, the first American combat mission in the war, takes place.

events.description: Rebels in Zanzibar begin a revolt known as the Zanzibar Revolution and proclaim a republic.
events.html: • 1964 – Rebels in Zanzibar begin a revolt known as the Zanzibar Revolution and proclaim a republic.

events.description: Lyndon B. Johnson states that the United States should stay in South Vietnam until Communist aggression there is ended.
events.html: • 1966 – Lyndon B. Johnson states that the United States should stay in South Vietnam until Communist aggression there is ended.

events.description: Dr. James Bedford becomes the first person to be cryonically preserved with intent of future resuscitation.
events.html: • 1967 – Dr. James Bedford becomes the first person to be cryonically preserved with intent of future resuscitation.

events.description: The New York Jets of the American Football League defeat the Baltimore Colts of the National Football League to win Super Bowl III in what is considered to be one of the greatest upsets in sports history.
events.html: • 1969 – The New York Jets of the American Football League defeat the Baltimore Colts of the National Football League to win Super Bowl III in what is considered to be one of the greatest upsets in sports history.

events.description: Biafra capitulates, ending the Nigerian Civil War.
events.html: • 1970 – Biafra capitulates, ending the Nigerian Civil War.

events.description: The Harrisburg Seven: Rev. Philip Berrigan and five other activists are indicted on charges of conspiring to kidnap Henry Kissinger and of plotting to blow up the heating tunnels of federal buildings in Washington, D.C.
events.html: • 1971 – The Harrisburg Seven: Rev. Philip Berrigan and five other activists are indicted on charges of conspiring to kidnap Henry Kissinger and of plotting to blow up the heating tunnels of federal buildings in Washington, D.C.

events.description: The United Nations Security Council votes 11–1 to allow the Palestine Liberation Organization to participate in a Security Council debate (without voting rights).
events.html: • 1976 – The United Nations Security Council votes 11–1 to allow the Palestine Liberation Organization to participate in a Security Council debate (without voting rights).

events.description: Space Shuttle program: Congressman and future NASA Administrator Bill Nelson lifts off from Kennedy Space Center aboard Columbia on mission STS-61-C as a payload specialist.
events.html: • 1986 – Space Shuttle program: Congressman and future NASA Administrator Bill Nelson lifts off from Kennedy Space Center aboard Columbia on mission STS-61-C as a payload specialist.

events.description: A seven-day pogrom breaks out against the Armenian civilian population of Baku, Azerbaijan, during which Armenians were beaten, tortured, murdered, and expelled from the city.
events.html: • 1990 – A seven-day pogrom breaks out against the Armenian civilian population of Baku, Azerbaijan, during which Armenians were beaten, tortured, murdered, and expelled from the city.

events.description: Space Shuttle program: Atlantis launches from the Kennedy Space Center on mission STS-81 to the Russian space station Mir, carrying astronaut Jerry M. Linenger for a four-month stay on board the station, replacing astronaut John E. Blaha.

events.html: • 1998 – Nineteen European nations agree to forbid human cloning.

events.html: • 2004 – The world's largest ocean liner, RMS Queen Mary 2, makes its maiden voyage.
